##The outbreak magnified the Samsung crisis, Vietnam Base lack of manpower, lack of materials, lack of coordination

It is almost impossible to set up a full-scale industrial chain in a country other than China, and the ability to hedge risks is limited

The Gist:

1. So far, six workers at Samsung's turtle tail factory in South Korea have been diagnosed with COVID-19, a new infection that began in February. On March 10, Samsung announced the closure of the Turtle Tail Plant to ensure that the outbreak did not spread.

2. To solve the shipping problem, Samsung is pinning its hopes on its production base in Vietnam. But Vietnam's capacity situation is tougher than expected.

3. In addition to a 14-day stay in a third country, Samsung's more than 1,000 engineers will be quarantined locally for another 14 days. Back and forth down, basically a delay of nearly a month's time.

4. Many suppliers'stocks in Vietnam last only two to four weeks, including cameras, a key component.

5. In 2018, several of Samsung's high-end flagship phones reached the top 10 in global sales of high-end phones; by 2019, however, most of the Samsung phones on the list were mid-to low-end models.

Samsung is suffering more than ever. Samsung Electronics reported net income of $18.5 billion in 2019, down 51 percent from a year earlier, and revenue of $195.6 billion, down 5.5 percent from a year earlier and the lowest since 2016. Samsung's mobile revenue fell 8.3% from a year earlier.

To boost its results, Samsung said in its earnings report that it would launch a number of high-end flagship phones by 2020, while strengthening its 5G lineup to make mid-and low-end phones more competitive.

But now the outbreak has disrupted production plans.

According to "CAIJING" reporters understand that due to the epidemic, Samsung's production base in China and Southeast Asia are affected to varying degrees. Under pressure, Samsung has already started cutting deals. A salesman for ODM  , a research and design company for Smart Terminals, told Caijing that Samsung had already cut back some of its orders. The reason is simple: So far, capacity at Huaqin's domestic plants has returned to just 50% .

Last November, Samsung closed its last mobile phone factory in Huizhou, China. Since then, Samsung has outsourced 20% of its shipments to ODM  , a Chinese giant, which makes mid to low range phones for Samsung that average about $60.

The Turtle Tail Factory in South Korea, which makes high-end phones for Samsung, is also out of production. The factory had planned to produce this year's flagship high end folding phones, the Galaxy Z Flip and the Galaxy S20. So far, six workers at the turtle tail factory have been diagnosed with COVID-19, a new infection that has been spreading inside the plant since February. On March 10, Samsung announced the closure of the Turtle Tail Plant to ensure that the outbreak did not spread.

The sudden change in production no doubt made things worse. To solve the shipping problem, Samsung is pinning its hopes on its production base in Vietnam. But Vietnam's capacity situation is tougher than expected.

Thousands of engineers can't get into Vietnam, materials can't keep up

Samsung has tried to shift some orders from Kamehame and its Chinese factories to Vietnam. Vietnam is now Samsung's largest manufacturing base in the world, producing more than half of Samsung's phones. According to Caijing, the factory has sent the required parts and semi-finished products to Vietnam as requested by Samsung.

But according to "CAIJING" reporters understand that under the current production conditions in Vietnam, Samsung wants to complete more orders in the short term, the challenge is very big. It's not Samsung's personality, it's Vietnam's manufacturing sector as a whole. Vietnam's Ministry of Industry and Trade said in a statement that manufacturers of cars, electronics and mobile phones had encountered difficulties in obtaining supplies and materials.

A source close to Samsung's supply chain told Caijing that new orders will require up to 1,000 engineers from South Korea to come to Vietnam for local support. But since the outbreak escalated in March, the Vietnamese government has abruptly tightened border controls on South Korea.

In addition to a 14-day stay in a third country, the engineers will be quarantined for another 14 days when they arrive locally. Back and forth down, basically a delay of nearly a month's time.

On the other hand, the epidemic has caused serious disruption of import and export logistics between China and Vietnam. After the Spring Festival, Friendship Pass, China's largest trade gateway, and its second-tier ports were closed. Although it is now gradually recovering through daily flow restrictions, the previous month had seen an accumulation of too much cargo, resulting in heavy traffic and inefficient delivery.

Many suppliers'stocks in Vietnam last only two to four weeks. Key components, including the camera,. A supply chain source told CAIJING that shunyu optics was originally the supplier of Samsung's camera modules, but since the domestic rework rate is only 30% , Samsung has started to change the supplier in desperation.

Although there are tens of thousands of Samsung suppliers in Vietnam, 30 per cent of the materials are still imported from China. Even if the phone could be assembled, it would not ship because of a lack of plugs, cables or even a printed label on the box.

According to the CAIJING reporter, including Lam SI, Bern and other local supporting factories are due to raw material supply problems, production capacity too late to restore normal. "Even if the orders were transferred, the Vietnamese side would not be able to digest them, " one of Samsung's second-tier suppliers in Vietnam, who provides packaging and printing services for Samsung phones, told Caijing.

Like many local suppliers, Samsung is not adding orders because of capacity, and the number is constantly changing. He expects first-quarter orders to be a third lower than planned.

Production transfer is easy, supply chain transfer is difficult

Samsung led the world in 2019 with 296 million units, followed by Huawei with about 240 million units, and apple with 190 million units, according to counterpoint, a market research firm. Despite years of being number one in mobile phone sales, Samsung reported an 8.3 per cent year-on-year decline in mobile profits in 2019.

The reason for the fall in profits is not hard to understand. Samsung's spending on marketing and promotion rose 5 percent to about $45 million in 2019, but sales of its high-end flagship machines, which drive the company's core profits, were sluggish.

Several of Samsung's high-end flagship phones, including the Galaxy S 9 and Galaxy S9 plus, made the top 10 in global sales in 2018, according to market research firm counterpoint. But by 2019, the Samsung phones on the list were the Galaxy A50, the Galaxy A20 and the Galaxy A10, all mid to low end models.

In fact, in 2019, Samsung introduced six high end flagship Galaxy phones, including four in the s series, one in the Note series, and a brand new line of folding screens, but none made the list. By comparison, Apple's iPhone 11 and iPhone 11pro are both in the top 10.

In order to optimize its profit structure, Samsung has been accelerating the shift of its manufacturing base over the past few years to further reduce production costs.

Since 2009, Samsung has set up eight factories and a research and Development Centre in Vietnam, at a total investment of more than $17.3 BN, accounting for a fifth of Vietnam's exports. In 2018, Vietnam processed $65.7 billion in electronics sales for Samsung, accounting for about 30 percent of Samsung's global electronics sales, according to the report.

After closing all of its mobile phone assembly plants in China last October, Samsung moved further to Vietnam, particularly in the high-end assembly segment.

But shifting production is easy; shifting supply chains is hard. This is because the mobile phone industry chain is so long that it is almost impossible to set up an entire industry chain outside of China. This means that even with cost savings, the ability to hedge risk is limited.

According to "CAIJING" reporters understand that more than 60% of Vietnam's local supply chain enterprises in the service of Samsung, but the completion of the basic are rough parts. Both Goel and Raytheon are core suppliers to Samsung. Since 2012, Samsung has required these tier one suppliers to set up shop in Vietnam to ensure quick response.

But the supply chain of electronic products is a network structure, the first-level suppliers below the second-level suppliers and many supporting links. More than 80 per cent of the material is imported, and only the Assembly is done in Vietnam, the local head of Goel told CAIJING. That's because the further up the supply chain you go, the harder it is to move, especially parts.

After closing its Huizhou Factory last October, Samsung moved a matching Korean screw factory to Vietnam, according to Caijing. But the rest of the screw factory's Chinese counterparts are difficult to move together, because the raw materials needed, such as plastic and steel, can not be produced locally. The cost and risk of logistics plus the cost of setting up a factory in Vietnam is high.

However, these front-end supply chain companies have also accelerated their moves abroad over the past year as a result of trade frictions between the US and China. Synthesize the observation of many supply chain enterprises, for tycoon, the safest way in the future is to do the layout of supply chain separately in many countries.
